results.occurrenceRemarks: Bird about the size of a Partridge, look like it was feeding among the flax leaves. Was quite calm and did not spook when I kayaked pass twice...  did slowly walk away, but was within a couple of meters of it.   Photo was taken with my phone, hence the terrible quality. Whenever I do not bring my camera I miss out on great photos.   Never seen one before.

Tallawarra Ash Pond 3, Yallah, Forming part of the area known as Tallawarra Lands, this site is lies between Yallah Bay Road to the north, the Princes Highway to the west and Haywards Bay Drive to the south. It was used as the dumping ground for ash from the coal-fired Tallawarra power station in the last years of its life between 1983 and 1989. The ash reaches a depth of 14 metres in places. Having largely been untouched since operations ceased, it is a haven for a wide range of birdlife and includes 4 bodies of water where the ash pond was not filled to capacity. Sadly most of the site is slated for development by the owner TRU Energy. Access can be obtained by first taking the site induction by arrangement with the owner, although some of the site is visible from Haywards Bay Drive.  (Note this incorporates the site currently listed as Haywards Bay Drive Wetland, Haywards Bay)
